@node sugges "A Note About Suggestions"

It could theoretically be possible to make the random icon sensitive to
the type of the file (i.e. IFF,MOD,etc) but it would warrant a @{b}complete@{ub}
rewrite of the code (and it wouldn't be so random anymore:-) If I hear
from enough users out there wanting this I will do my best to make it
work. I would call this 'CnDefIco' short for Certain Default Icon and
I'm afraid that I really WOULD place that into shareware unless something
really nice would turn my thoughts around. (CnDefIco would, as I said, be
a lot of work.)
@endnode

@node What "What is RnDefIco?"

In Workbench 2.0 and higher the WB creates icons for objects that don't have
icons if the user so wants. It creates these icons from default icons depending
on the type of the object. I.e. it creates a certain looking file icon for all
files and a certain looking directory icon for directories. The duller these
icons look the faster the fact, that they all look the same, will become
annoying.

	The Solution: RnDefIco

The name (Random Default Icon) really says it all, but I'll say it too so that
it all becomes clear: RnDefIco patches itself into the depths of WB (actually
to the depths icon.library) and every time WB (or any other program for that
matter) needs a default icon RnDefIco gives a random one to it.

	'Your WB will never be boring again.' :-)
@endnode

@node Install "How to install RnDefIco "

First you need to drop RnDefIco-icon into the WBStartup-drawer.
Then you need to create a file that has the paths and names of all the icons
that you want RnDefIco to use in it. The default name for the prefs file is:

		ENV:RnDefIco.prefs

so you should create a file called:

		ENVARC:RnDefIco.prefs

If you want to use another file instead you have to add a tooltype called
MICON=«filename» to RnDefIco's icon. (Example:  MICON=ENV:RnDefIco.prefs  )

An example prefs file is included in the example drawer, but this file only
includes the icons that you are already using. All the icon example drawers
also include an example prefs file to work with them.
@endnode

@node Docs "RnDefIco documentation"

RnDefIco is not a commodity and the user interface (= prefs-file) is not very
pleasant, but if I get enough responses I will 'right these two wrongs'.

RnDefIco reads its prefs file a line at a time and tries to open an icon of
the name that is on the line. If it succeeds it adds the icon among others of
it's kind (i.e. it automatically recognizes disk.icons for disk.icons and
drawer.icons for drawer.icons etc where ever they are) This means that you can
write anything you want into the prefs file just as long as the real icons have
paths and start at the very beginning of the line. Also I think it would be
best if your comments didn't have colons (:) in them, because the system would
demand a disk called 'your comment:' in any drive :-(

To stop RnDefIco (who would want that?) just send a 'CTRL-F' or
signal 0x00008000 to it. (clumsy isn't it)
@endnode

@node Credits


RnDefIco was written by Aleksi Suhonen with some [:-) help of SAS/C 6.50
